 - Is it the cat that drinks Evian,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.120
 or is it the owner who feeds the cat Evian?

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:10.840
 (laughing)

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:13.440
 - Wow, yeah, I'm gonna get defensive now.

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:14.520
 (laughing)

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:15.680
 - It does know James.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:18.280
 - Yeah, I think this is completely reasonable though,

00:05:18.280 --> 00:05:19.880
 because what is apart from, you know,

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:22.040
 an artist creates a work of art of whatever kind,

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:25.640
 and then the viewer engages with it in whatever way.

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:26.760
 And if you're thinking about it,

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:27.920
 and if it's more conceptual,

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:30.360
 it's harder to get your head around.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:31.800
 - And there is always the question of,

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:33.000
 does this painting mean something,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:34.840
 or does it mean nothing?

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:37.880
 And I didn't know about disembration,

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:39.720
 the art movement, disembration.

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:40.560
 - I don't know that game.

00:05:40.560 --> 00:05:42.040
 - Which is the epitome of this.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:43.200
 It's so cool.

00:05:43.200 --> 00:05:45.640
 So this is an art movement that was started in 1924

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:49.080
 by an artist called Pavel Gerdanovich,

00:05:49.080 --> 00:05:52.520
 and he created this painting called Exaltation,

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:56.120
 which is of a woman holding a sort of floppy banana tree,

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:57.760
 starfish-y type thing,

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:00.200
 and a tilting hut in the background.

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:02.320
 And it became very popular, it was reviewed,

00:06:02.320 --> 00:06:05.200
 and it looks a bit like kind of naive art, right?

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.160
 - Yeah, what it looks exactly like is,

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:09.920
 do you remember that mural that was defaced

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:11.640
 by women trying to fix it a few years ago?

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:13.000
 - The picture of Christ, okay, almost.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.800
 - Yeah, I thought it looked a lot like that, do you not think?

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:16.800
 - Yeah.

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:18.160
 - So I thought a lot like Gogan.

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:20.040
 - Well, I would say a lot of his others like Gogan,

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:21.760
 but anyway, this guy was not an artist,

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:23.400
 he was a guy called Paul Jordan Smith,

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:25.640
 who was pissed off at people like Picasso,

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:27.360
 who he thought were impenetrable,

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:29.720
 and his wife happened to have done some still life,

00:06:29.720 --> 00:06:30.800
 which were very realistic,

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:32.720
 that hadn't been very well received.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.800
 And so he said something like,

00:06:34.800 --> 00:06:36.400
 I've made up my mind that critics will praise

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:37.880
 anything unintelligible.

00:06:37.880 --> 00:06:40.000
 So he painted this exaltation,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.120
 and it is, I suppose, bad,

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:46.000
 but there were art journals, like posh art journals,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.040
 who, one of the best quote I thought was

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:51.640
 from the French journal, of course,

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:53.520
 the review of the true and the beautiful

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:56.200
 that said, Pavel Jardinavitch is not satisfied

00:06:56.200 --> 00:06:58.000
 to follow ordinary paths.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.200
 His spirit delights in intoxication,

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:01.880
 and he has prayed to the aesthetic agonies,

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.280
 which are not experienced without suffering.

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:07.000
 And then in 1927, he went, I was taking the piss, guys.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:08.880
 I thought some of his were actually okay.

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:10.920
 Even knowing he was meaning to be silly.

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:13.080
 - Actually, did you like it more

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:15.280
 because you knew the story maybe?

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:16.840
 Because that is a thing.

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:19.760
 So there was a study where people were shown

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:21.600
 painted by Van Gogh,

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.080
 and they said, what do you think of it?

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:27.240
 And half of them were told, it's just by Van Gogh,

00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:28.720
 and the other half were told,

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:31.000
 oh, this is by Van Gogh, who cuts his air off.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.200
 And the people who were told

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.000
 that he cuts his air off liked it more,

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:37.840
 because their artist is slightly wacky,

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:40.400
 and I think that's, yeah, again, it absolutely makes sense.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.760
 Like, for example, when I make jokes,

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:44.200
 if I have a story behind them

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:45.960
 as to why the joke is there.

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:49.160
 - When have you ever had a compelling story

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:50.160
 behind Eddie of your jokes?

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:51.800
 - Well, that's what I need, clearly.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:53.960
 People would laugh a lot more if I said,

00:07:53.960 --> 00:07:55.640
 and I'm cutting my air off right now.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:57.440
 - Wait, so do you think we would actually think

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:58.840
 one of your cop dramas is good

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.920
 if you came in with a missing ear lobe?

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:01.920
 - Oh, there's no question.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:02.760
 - Right.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:04.880
 - A guy in an alley cut off my ear,

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:07.080
 but it gave me this amazing idea.

00:08:07.080 --> 00:08:09.080
 - Def Echo Cop.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:09.920
 - Yes.

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:10.840
 (laughing)

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:11.680
 - Yes.

00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:15.160
 You only said yes once there, but it bouts not well.

00:08:15.160 --> 00:08:16.920
 (laughing)

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:18.160
 - But this is a thing, isn't it?

00:08:18.160 --> 00:08:20.920
 Tortured artist is a thing that we get drawn to,

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:22.160
 the story behind the artist,

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:24.080
 and they have done a few studies

00:08:24.080 --> 00:08:27.840
 where they've shown portraits and general artwork

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.080
 from the artists from different periods of their life,

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:31.880
 and weirdly, when they voted on them,

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:34.600
 they voted for the ones that were not done

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:37.880
 in a point of mental anguish from the artist's point.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:38.720
 - Oh, really?

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:40.480
 - And they voted that the better one.

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:44.480
 So it's interesting that it sort of doesn't correlate

00:08:44.480 --> 00:08:45.840
 with their tortured art as this.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:46.680
 - Oh, wow.

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:47.960
 - You're saying when someone is calm and happy and productive,

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:49.400
 that's actually when they're doing the best work.

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:51.760
 According to this, that's really interesting.

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:54.040
 - One encouraging thing I think about this whole torture

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.160
 artist thing is AI can probably already do art

00:08:57.160 --> 00:08:59.800
 better than any human on Earth, right?

00:08:59.800 --> 00:09:03.080
 But people really care about the stories

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:04.840
 behind the people doing the work.

00:09:04.840 --> 00:09:09.440
 And so even if my painting of a unicorn with three legs

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:13.240
 is not quite as good as one that chat GPT can do,

00:09:13.240 --> 00:09:15.880
 if people know that I did it because my daughter loves

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:17.400
 a unicorns and I love my daughter,

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:20.120
 then they're going to think that it's a better work of art

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:21.320
 than the thing that the company does.

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.560
 - Yeah, the question, as in--

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:24.520
 - Well, I'm going to think it's incredibly now.

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:25.360
 - Right.

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:26.200
 (all laughing)

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:28.080
 - Yeah, that's why your art journal folded,

00:09:28.080 --> 00:09:30.080
 and it's like, this is all shit.

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:32.280
 But this is the really interesting thing

00:09:32.280 --> 00:09:35.800
 about how technically good quite a quite a work of art is,

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:37.640
 'cause it's not about whether it's an accurate

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:39.800
 or a realistic drawing of a unicorn.

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.320
 And this all relates to the early 20th century

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:44.960
 when photography was coming in in a big way, right?

00:09:44.960 --> 00:09:46.720
 A century before that, if you could paint

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:49.360
 an incredibly good picture of a lemon,

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:50.720
 you were set for life, right?

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:53.120
 - There would be like, this guy paints bloody good lemons.

00:09:53.120 --> 00:09:55.240
 - I mean, it looks like a lemon, you know?

00:09:55.240 --> 00:09:56.880
 - Have you seen Sicilian Dream?

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:58.560
 - It's extremely-- - It's true, right.

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.600
 And then when photography comes along,

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:02.280
 there's this question of, oh, right,

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:03.720
 photography's kind of eating our lunch here.

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:06.640
 So art becomes more conceptual, partly as a response

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:09.160
 to the fact that you can now just get photos of things.

00:10:09.160 --> 00:10:10.720
 - Yeah, I had to talk about that, okay.

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:13.080
 - And then that is when you get more titles coming in

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:15.920
 because the art has become more conceptual

00:10:15.920 --> 00:10:18.360
 and you're getting more like theoretical work

